flavor_text: It drains vitality from those it touches.
"Good girl."
"Your precious laws can't save you now!"
It was made for battle, but that doesn't mean it's unsophisticated.
"We're finished here."
"Hold it! I need to see your papers."

"One beginning, many paths."
â€”Vannifar

Shhh . . .

"You take our wilds, we take your city."
"Do not think me blind to your true mission...or your true master, Grand Arbiter."

A Gruul berserker is never unarmed.
The sly, stealthy warriors of the Slizt Clan survive by hiding in high ground and ambushing their enemies. Other Gruul call them skulkers and cowards, but only from a safe distance.
Some view Domri's unlikely ascent as a sign of Ilharg the Raze-Boar's imminent return.
"Entertain me."

"That one has a bright futureâ€”perfect instincts for the rhythm of mayhem."
â€”Judith

"I told Jace that Ravnica would fall apart if he didn't take his responsibilities seriously. I didn't want to be right."

At the end of the show, she stands alone on a stage brilliant with blood.
The rights of ghosts are strictly protected under Orzhov bylaws, and those who enforce them can count on the ghosts' assistance.
Havoc is a small price to pay for data.
"They all want to see me fall."
"As I contemplate what is, I dive ever deeper into the depths of possibility. Then I set an experiment in motion and watch the truth rise to the surface."
She displays her scars with pride.
Cyclical and spiral patterns are the specialty of the Gyre Clade, which seeks to revitalize the cycles of nature.
"Debt due! Debt due!" The thrull's screeching makes children flinch and debtors quail. "Debt due!"

"Vraska sees the grandeur in death but misses the hilarity."
â€”Judith

"I might have overfed him."
â€”Gulistan, Simic biomancer
"Your arrival was expected...and unwelcome."
"Let's find out what kind of audience you are. Festive? Fearless?"

"Time to let the dead be dead."
â€”Kaya, to Teysa

Jaharg discovered that the shapes and symmetries so pleasing to the sculptor's eye also yielded a well-balanced bludgeon.

"It's easy to get taken in by the spectacle, to enjoy a bit of naughty amusement. But make no mistake: the Cult of Rakdos is a danger."
â€”Tajic
You can hear their tolling only when your debt is due.
"These new thopters are all well and good, but four eyes are better than none."
Thanks to the magic of his Writ of Passage, alms beasts lumbered aside, anarchs bowed their heads, and even Rakdos acrobats rolled their spikewheels out of his way.

"The absence of binocular vision imposes certain challenges for a flying creature, which are overcome via echolocation."
â€”Simic research notes
"In your misguided attempt to subvert the law, you have eloquently explained why the law must exist."

"The best construction makes the most satisfying destruction."
â€”Domri Rade

"Walls crack. Buildings fall. Always the wilds return."

â€”Korun Nar, Rubblebelt hunter

"The presence of the strong will make you stronger."

"What you build, we will destroy . . . and bury you in the rubble!"

â€”Vannifar
"Stay close! It's just a little farther."

"Within each of us, the potential for great power waits to be released."
â€”Zija, Simic mutationist
"I hold the seed of our new beginning."

â€”Alcarus, Selesnya sagittar

"When you get right down to it, the difference between death and life is just a membrane-enclosed environment maintained by a metabolic process."
â€”Gulistan, Simic biomancer

"Rage! Rage until the whole world burns!"

â€”Tamina, district guide

â€”Bell Migellic, Azorius hussar

"There's no time to calm it down! Run!"

"Smash this city to pieces."

"To survive exceptional times we must adapt by exceptional means."

"My shout is thunder and my fist is lightning!"

"Don't waste time aiming, you lazy gob-slug! Fire!"
â€”Krenko, mob boss
"Come in, yes? Is warm!"

"Have you seen your face? Trust me, this will be an improvement."

"Places, everyone!"
â€”Judith
"Hello, kindling."

"No peace accord will save Ravnica. You don't build on rot. You burn it down and start again."

"Today the Rubblebelt is a bit larger. That's a good day's work."

"Fire will cure a multitude of ills."

"Lost are the lush meadows and verdant forests, where maaka prowled and lammasu soared. Lost are the wilds, where our hearts were free."
â€”Daiva, Gruul storyteller

"Leave no stone unturned."
â€”Ruric Thar
"Keep coming. I have knives enough for everyone."

â€”Ruric Thar

"From a great bonfire at the dawn of time, the first Gruul kindled their rage. The same flame burns in you."
â€”Kroshkar, Gruul shaman
Seen through Rakdos eyes, a cruel betrayal is a hilarious stunt.

The undercity is always hungry.

"We grow strong by feasting on failure."
â€”Izoni

"Your life is a blinding light, your breath a gale, your pulse a deafening drum. Be still. Be still."
â€”Dahlya Trul, "Irbitov Lament"

"The louder their performance, the quieter we become in comparison. They are the perfect distractions, for only fools ignore the Rakdos."
â€”Lazav

For some goods, the best couriers are the dead.
Its stench corrodes steel. Its miasma sickens angels. Its finality ends hope.
"Looks like you need protection."
"You'll pay what you owe, with your money or your life."

"Behold the groodion! Ichor-slurper, oozing fiend. Foulest wonder underground. Grandest vermin of them all!"
â€”Zalin the Gutter Bard
"The suffering of others is not my concern."

â€”Nicol Bolas
Never boring.
By design, the sarcophagus muffles the debtors' moans but does not silence them.

If your ears bleed, it's a party. If your eyes bleed, it's a Rakdos party.
First your whole life flashes before your eyes. Then you have considerable time to reflect on every regret as you plummet.
"Make way! It's time for the final act!"

No scrap of nutrition goes to waste in the undercity.
Blood seeks blood, and nothing shall hold back its hunger.

"The pain of searing iron and razor edges pales beside the pleasure of performance."

"Your spirits can rest in peace, for your debts are paid."

"Here, there is only truth."
â€”Barvisa, Azorius emissary

"I can think of no greater punishment than answering your question in full."

â€”Grupgrup, sluiceway technician

"To control the present we must master the future."

"They've got eyes inside my head!"

"It's not enough to defeat our foes. We must learn from them, too."

â€”Lazav
If you can see your breath, it's too late to run.
"I am my life's work."
Law is the voice of reason.

"I keep reminding myself we do this because others can't, because we love this city. If we don't save it, no one will."

"Many wings haunt the skies these days. Few of them bear good tidings."

Guardian Project biomancer

A ray of hope breaks through the shroud of rain.

"If we cannot have peace, we will have justice."
â€”Aurelia

Their fires burn quietly, allowing the phoenixes to glide silently through the canyon.

"No single arrow can pierce an entire flock."
The ultimate answer to intrigue and subtlety.

â€”Izzet research notes

â€”Vraska

"People would sooner savor sweet lies than chew plain truths."

"There is nothing stronger than many hearts united for a single cause."

Feed on food, you eventually rot. Feed on rot, you live forever.

"Please don't feed the beetles."

"The route is direct but challenging. Incidentally, how are you with heights?"

"Don't stop till your horns come out their back."

"The power that flows here cannot be denied. But where is the source?" â€”Nissa Revane
They are tasked with protecting the entrance to the embalming chambers.

"When the Second Sun rests between the horns on the horizon, so begins the Hour of Revelation. Then the Hour of Glory, the Hour of Promise, and finally the Hour of Eternity." â€”The Accounting of Hours
"The worthy shall hone a strong body to endure the boundless energies of the afterlife." â€”Monument inscription
Five gods, one purpose.
"The worthy shall respect the worthy. In the afterlife, all will stand united." â€”Monument inscription
Without the God-Pharaoh, there would be no Luxa. Without the Luxa, there would be no life.
"The worthy shall cultivate a nimble mind to perceive the glorious wonders that await them." â€”Monument inscription
Blades and bravery go hand in hand.
"The worthy shall rush to the God-Pharaoh's side with relentless zeal, rising to overcome every obstacle." â€”Monument inscription
"They might be dead, but these mummies are masters of their trade." â€”Jace Beleren
"The worthy shall strive for greatness. Supremacy in life leads to supremacy in the afterlife." â€”Monument inscription
"Your waters sustain the living and carry the dead. Mighty Luxa, let your power flow through me!"
If one of the anointed fails to serve with perfect obedience, the desert is always ready to receive it.
She can coil a breeze like a string around her fingerâ€”or twist it into a noose.
"I'll fight no more just for the honor of dying. The afterlife will have to wait."
"My mind is the calm in the midst of the storm, and my javelin the lightning."
"We do not swerve." â€”Tah-crop charioteer motto
Her words inspire action. Her actions inspire victory.
Her subtle smile is suffused with venom.
Many initiates believe it possesses secrets known only to Kefnet himself. Many have become meals trying to learn them.
"The Second Sun nears its destination! Let it light the way to ours!"
The forked tongue of the naga is sensitive to drifting scent trails from the past, present, and sometimes even the future.
"Instincts to guide. Strength to overcome."
Khenra are almost always born as twins. Their instinctual connection lends itself well to their preferred fighting style.
Initiates must train to resist the natural toxins they use as weapons.
There are no safe paths through the Trial of Strength.
Instinct yields the truest insight.
To prepare for the Trial of Strength, nagas shed their old skinâ€”and with it their scars, their doubts, and their fears.
Surviving an encounter with it is proof enough that an initiate is ready for the Trial of Strength.
Cantankerous and territorial, sandwurms claim even the skies above their dunes.
They labor beside the anointed, constructing the vast monuments of Naktamun.
The viziers serving Rhonas, the god of strength, maintain the menagerie of animals employed during his trial.
Rhonas's monument is home to a wider variety of creatures than anywhere else in the city of Naktamunâ€”a feature most initiates fail to appreciate.
Debate rages among the viziers whether comparing the kudu's horns to the God-Pharaoh's is blasphemy or reverence.
"Like fruits in the field, we will be harvested when the season is right."
"The lands of the God-Pharaoh are suffused with his breath."
"Rely too much on your weapons and watch your dreams shatter in your hands." â€”Rhonas, god of strength
"I'd like to say that it's our pet, but the reverse may be closer to the truth." â€”Ixor, initiate of Rhet crop
Nagas wielding twin daggers excel at the fighting technique known as the Bite of Rhonas.
Even gods have pets.
Few can overcome an assault of such aggressive serenity.
A true reflection of nature: death fostering life.
"If you fear poisons, it is because you are ignorant of them." â€”Hapatra, vizier of poisons
A sandwurm can lie in wait beneath the sands for years until the slightest tremor alerts it to the presence of prey.
The Broken Lands are littered with the remnants of civilizations long dead and infested by terrors very much alive.
"No one is born worthy."
"When all doubts have melted away, the worthy will meet the Hour of Eternity and earn a place at the God-Pharaoh's side." â€”The Accounting of Hours
"Everything in the trial has teeth. You will overcome them, or you will feed them." â€”Rhonas, god of strength
"If it is bigger, you must be faster. If it is stronger, you must be sharper. Anything less, and you will never seize a place in our God-Pharaoh's perfect afterlife." â€”Rhonas, god of strength
The only way to finish the Trial of Strength is with a basilisk scale in hand.
"The vizier of poisons teaches an unconventional kind of strength."
It falls to the gods to help all become worthy of the afterlife.
Minotaurs favor magic that manifests as weapons wrapped in flame.
Initiates in the heat of combat must be able to adapt to changing conditions.
Shoulder to shoulder until blade must turn against blade.
"Eternal glory awaits you, my child."
"You are undeserving of the afterlife. You will never feel the God-Pharaoh's embrace."
The sound of its plated tail beating on desert rocks is often mistaken for the footfalls of a much larger predator.
The Hekma may repel storms and monsters, but nothing holds back the heat of the suns.
"Combat is a form of worship, the clash of steel a solemn prayer." â€”Pytamun, initiate of Nef crop
"The expected way through the trial is far too tedious."
"In the Hour of Glory, the gods and the untested will prove their worth before the God-Pharaoh." â€”The Accounting of Hours
"If you do not feel the thrill of battle, alive like a flame, you will never triumph."
"Those wings are no advantage. I will pin them to the ceiling of the Hekma."
In the training ground known as the Gauntlet, initiates are pushed to practice more destructive techniques.
"Ashes can't be embalmed." â€”Neheb, initiate of Ahn crop
"When the time comes, only one of you will be honored by my spear." â€”Hazoret, god of zeal
With carrion a rarity in the Broken Lands, the hyenas that stalk the deserts hunt in packs.
Hazoret's gift is bestowed only once.
"Fight through it."
What the initiates face in the final trial is completely at Hazoret's discretion.
Never flinch. Never falter. Never fear.
"Allow zealous flames to light your path and the glory you seek will be revealed." â€”Hazoret, god of zeal
"My stride will break only against the twin points of Hazoret's spear."
"Some hid from the storm. I embraced it and learned its name."
The endless expanse of desert surrounding Naktamun sometimes yields threats that the gods themselves must answer.
Headlong is the only way to pass through the gate to the afterlife.
The fifth cartouche is the final affirmation of glory, granted only to the worthy dead.
"Dissent? Your gods can't even begin to comprehend the dissent that's about to happen here!" â€”Chandra Nalaar
"Oketra had our crop build an obelisk to prove the power of working together. But I am stronger without the weak."
To Hazoret, those who fight for her are her beloved children.
"To victory! To glory! To eternity!"
The arrows fell like fiery rain, and for a moment, the sky itself seemed to burn.
"Hesitation breeds dissension. To be worthy of the next life, you must never look back." â€”Anep, vizier of Hazoret
All but the gods fear the scorpion's sting.
Forever restless. Forever growing in number.
"Ambition requires clarity. If you have any doubts, they must be abandoned." â€”Bontu, god of ambition
Even in the relative safety of the city, there are places best left undisturbed.
"All are not equalâ€”neither in life nor after death. Bontu's favorites will stand highest in eternity." â€”Senifet, vizier of Bontu
"Wherever you are in the city, you can feel the presence of the God-Pharaoh. Take comfort in that." â€”Ukhat, vizier of initiation
"Death has seeped into every part of this plane. I can feel it on my skin and taste it like sand in my mouth." â€”Nissa Revane
"The face of mediocrity is wrapped in anointed linen. Aspire to a better end." â€”Epnokep, vizier of Bontu
"You may feel a slight sting."
"You wish to remember this lesson? I will write it down for you." â€”Senifet, vizier of Bontu
"They are small, but they always want more. Learn from them." â€”Bontu, god of ambition
Its breath doesn't assault the senses. It pollutes the mind.
The Curse of Wandering leaves only hatred.
"There are so many of them. It seems they've just been waiting for someone to serve."
"True intentions lie not in the head but in the heart." â€”Bontu, god of ambition
It feeds on dry bones in the sand and desperate pleas in the wind.

"As a child I saw something walking in the distance, far beyond the Hekmaâ€”shadow-dark, and taller than the gods. Even now, it passes through my dreams."
â€”Pytamun, initiate of Nef crop
In Amonkhet's ever-shifting sands, nothing stays buried for long.
Those who earn a glorious death are given the highest honor. They are carried on funeral barges through the gate to the afterlife.
As its parched flesh withers away, its malignant hunger grows.
"The more I see of this place, the less I want to." â€”Chandra Nalaar
The scouring sands of Shefet polish its carapace, and the ranks of the cursed fill its belly.
There is only one fate left to those banished from the God-Pharaoh's city.
"Look! That is why we must never waver. That is what awaits us if we fail." â€”Djeru, initiate of Tah crop
As Gideon watched the initiate murder his crop-mate, his admiration of the city of Naktamun gave way to horror.
They are the first to greet dissenters on their journey into exile.
Amonkhet's dual suns don't allow for the darkness of night, so bats are most active under the gloom of the frequent sandstorms.
"Not all in our crop deserve the afterlife. We must leave the unworthy behind, Samut." â€”Djeru, initiate of Tah crop
Only from the sky can one fully understand the horrors of the wastes and the wonder of the Hekma's protection.
"I have foreseen that you will not pass my trial."
"Time is like the Luxa Riverâ€”though it flows in one direction, it can be diverted."
Initiates live and train with their crop, the unit that begins the trials together.
Some naga initiates move as silently as the suns' reflections on the water.
They are drawn by the brilliant blue glint of the mineral lazotep from the mines below.
The Trial of Knowledge challenges and broadens the minds of initiates.
"The best answers solve more than one riddle." â€”Kefnet, god of knowledge
The anointed work the mines without pause, their cartouches instilling them with tireless purpose.
Though the Luxa River brings life to Naktamun, it's not without dangers.
"I do things in my own time." â€”Etha, initiate of Rhet crop
The one thing the Gatewatch didn't expect to find on a plane ruled by Nicol Bolas was perfection.
Understanding is a matter of perspective.
"All questions will be answered during the Hour of Revelation."
Initiates need worry only about the trials. Everything else is in the hands of the gods.
"No amount of strength can help you overcome my trial. You must be ready to forgo your body and favor your mind." â€”Kefnet, god of knowledge
"The answers are here. This is the way through the trial."
"The God-Pharaoh created the Hekma to protect us from the horrors beyond and to surround us in his love."
Strong wings make strong winds.
"It usually appears placid, but don't be fooled. The Luxa River is a snake, and it can swallow you whole." â€”Neponem, vizier of Kefnet
Dependence on luck is anathema to Kefnet's rigorous studies. Those who hope to escape his maze by chance never succeed.
"If you want to truly test your survival skills, walk the Obelisk Path when the drakes are feeding." â€”Etha, initiate of Rhet crop
"Eyes see only what is possible. A trained mind can explore the impossible." â€”Kefnet, god of knowledge
To consult a sphinx is a test in patience. Perhaps that's the point.
It slithers through the senses, constricting consciousness and poisoning perceptions.
"How can there be doubt in the presence of such blessings?" â€”Ukhat, vizier of initiation
"Why so many questions?" â€”Temmet, vizier of Naktamun
Cartouches chronicle the initiates' achievements in the trials.
"Let me try one of Kefnet's puzzles. This one was too easy."
From the time they are hatchlings, river drakes are taught to pull the largest prey from the Luxa.
The banks of the Luxa River attract all manner of predator but only the most resilient of prey.
"When the Hour of Promise arrives, the God-Pharaoh will tear down the Hekma, for its protection will be needed no longer." â€”The Accounting of Hours
"You'll need all your strength for the trials to come."
"You will succeed as one or fail as many."
"Occasionally, there are those who refuse to appreciate all that the God-Pharaoh provides for us." â€”Temmet, vizier of Naktamun

"The dead perform all the work hereâ€”farming, building, teaching, even embalming their fellow mummies. The living need do nothing but train. What system could be more perfect?" â€”Temmet, vizier of Naktamun
"We each have a weight to carry on the road to the afterlife." â€”Oketra, god of solidarity
Aspiring to earn their place in the afterlife, acolytes train every day against those who fell short of that glory.
"Angels? My feelings remain unchanged." â€”Liliana Vess
"In the afterlife, I'll have no need of sleep. And until then, I have no time for it!"
"To see gods among the people, part of their daily lives . . . It's inspiring."
Oketra's closest viziers are known as her chosen, though others may have a better claim to that moniker.
Part of the acolytes' training is to walk along the Hekma, staring out at the ravenous horrors kept at bay by the God-Pharaoh's barrier.
"I feel the presence of the God-Pharaoh in the Second Sun, and I rise upon its rays."
"A single grain of sand is insignificant, but a sandstorm can reduce pyramids to dust. Stand with your crop. Become the storm." â€”Oketra, god of solidarity
To a trained warrior, there is scarcely a more potent weapon than patience.
"I'm never unarmed."
"Fly as an arrow through the trials, and never waver in your course." â€”Oketra, god of solidarity
"Why cling to these trappings? They are but tools and affectations. True wealth can be possessed only in the afterlife."
Rest sometimes requires the right prompting.
"When I wish to be strong, I train. When I wish to be wise, I study. When I wish to rest, I start again."
The pain of death is nothing compared to the pain of failure.
What the gods decree, the mummies enforce.
"The only question we need to ask is how best to fulfill the will of the God-Pharaoh."
"The gods here may walk among the people, but they are not with them." â€”Gideon Jura

flavor_text: "We are the hands of the great trees, reaching out to ensnare what threatens their branches." â€”Elvish hunter
The quickest way to get through the jungle is to agitate a rhino and run in its wake.
In the Jamuraan jungles, there is often no separating beauty from danger.
They make terrible pets â€¦ unless you don't like your other pets.

"You should have seen the look on both their faces."
â€”Morkamp, Lambholt innkeeper

"When the beast cloaks itself in the mighty oak, what good is a bow? When the oak wraps itself around the snarling beast, what good is a hatchet?"
â€”Dionus, elvish archdruid
The giant was felt a few seconds before he was seen.
The undisputed master of the mountains of Shiv.

"Each day there are new reports of homes along Getander Pass and Hofsaddel falling to vampires of a more savage nature. I've even heard tell that Anje Falkenrath has returned. Please send whatever help you can." â€”Sterin Gorn, letter to Thalia
"Mindlessness is not weakness. When we are lost to hunger we are unstoppable." â€”Drana, Kalastria bloodchief
Empires rise and fall, but evil is eternal.
The earth cannot hold that which magic commands.
The thunder of its hooves beats dreams into despair.
Some spirits cling to one person, feasting on the growing fear until a final moment of all-consuming terror.
It returns eager to share the feast of blood and gore with its ghoulish master.
"Pathetic. You might as well have protected your treasures with a paper box and some string."
The Dimir would hire her, if only they knew where she lived. The Azorius would condemn her, if only they knew her name.
"A riddle is nothing more than a trap for small minds, baited with the promise of understanding."
"Day 31: I finally succeeded in my time reversal experiment! "Day 30: I might have a problem here." â€”Journal of the Prime Izmagnus
Some took to their boats to escape the unfolding nightmare. The remains of their vessels now litter the shores of Nephalia.
Merfolk are best known for their subtle magic. But those who try to fight them in their own territory quickly realize that merfolk are hardly defenseless on the field of battle.
Pray that it doesn't seek the safety of your lungs.
Its hooves touch the earth only when a hero must rise.
"Bant sentries were called the Angel Line. They never faltered, and they were ready to die defending their position." â€”Elspeth Tirel
Follow the light. In its absence, follow her.
"There's no contract to sign, no oath to swear. The enlistment procedure is to unsheathe your sword and point it at the enemy."
"Guilty."
Aether currents in the sky mirror water currents below, including the deadly rapids.
Tezzeret's command of living metal has nothing to do with intricate gearcraft or aether supplies.
Its elaborate designs reveal secrets of aether's flow.
"You can't hope to comprehend the plans that are in motion." â€”Tezzeret
Beyond the chaos of Ghirapur lies a vibrant world where aether flows through nature.
"I will go where the lion-man leads."
"This is about more than aether or inventions. Tezzeret's schemes must be stopped!" â€”Ajani Goldmane
A beacon of prosperity to some, a shadow of oppression to others.
Most of the constructs the renegades used against the Consulate weren't originally intended for combat. But some didn't require much modification.
"Before we can destroy our enemies, we must find them. We must peer into every wretched hovel and every teeming market." â€”Baral, Chief of Compliance
"A perfect fusion of nature and artifice." â€”Irsi, Kujar gardener
Rules and rails are made to be broken.
"A few drops of this, and the trickiest problems simply melt away." â€”Thamaz, Weldfast inventor
The Consulate prizes innovation when it is dependable and replicable.
Renegade supply lines are, by necessity, mobile and difficult to disrupt.
"We have safe houses in every zone, but you'll never find one without this."

The Scrappers, an underground group with a passion for automaton brawls, had renegade leanings even before the Consulate's crackdown. It didn't take long for them to lend their best brawlers to the conflict.
"It is finished. Now the real work can begin." â€”Tezzeret
"Peace? Its sole purpose is fear." â€”Saheeli Rai
"One look at this glorious item convinced me that Kaladesh deserved my full attention. Sure enough, my time here has yielded exquisite fruit." â€”Tezzeret
The Consulate had access to thousands of innovative devices displayed at the Inventors' Fair. A few small changes transformed some of them from marvels of ingenuity to instruments of oppression.
"You want to know what we are fighting for? Look at the wonder in that child's eyes." â€”Pia Nalaar
"One head watches for Consulate enforcers. The other watches for renegade thieves." â€”Crime Lord Gonti
"If you can build it, we can move it." â€”Bes Tavani, Bomat merchant
"Inspiration is found by looking outward." â€”Oviya Pashiri, sage lifecrafter
"We've been through a lot together."
Ghirapur's most celebrated inventors have been immortalized in clockwork.
A mystery in metal.
A tool to see the unseen.
A dream of fire lies coiled inside, waiting for its glorious awakening.
The renegades mounted an aether disruptor aboard a lightweight thopter to destroy Tezzeret's Planar Bridge.
Despite the magic that sustains Gonti's life, the crime lord is often described as heartless.
"They never tire, they never complain, and they never ask questions. Build more." â€”Ivash, Consulate inventor
"The most harmonious designs are based on relationships found in nature." â€”Venand Kapur, the Gearherder
"All buildings are subject to search. Resistance will be punished." â€”Enforcer-Chief Ranaj
"Our watchtowers are well positioned. Why don't we arm them?" â€”Enforcer-Chief Ranaj
"It's like they planted another Bastion right in the middle of the harbor." â€”Bes Tavani, Bomat merchant
Duplication is neither thievery nor flattery. It is efficiency.
"The Consulate sought to crush us. Let's give them a taste of their own medicine." â€”Venkat Dasai, renegade commander
When you have taught an automaton how to build others of its kind, it is a small step to make it build itself.
The streets of Ghirapur have become dangerous. It's good to have a dependable companion.
"Let's err on the side of glorious mayhem."
"After I examine your cargo and check your papers, you can be on your way."
"It's natural, it's all around us, and it's there for the taking. Just try and tell me what I'm doing is wrong."
Many veterans of the Ovalchase racetrack turned their talents to the renegade cause.
"This fight belongs to us all."
The vibrant forest of Peema is awash with aether. Its animals are stronger, faster, and more aggressive than their counterparts elsewhere.
"Until all have found their place, I will keep watch."
"If the Consulate has abandoned restraint, so too shall the wilds." â€”Surash, keeper of the Cowl
Elvish weavers use spidersilk to make everything from tapestries to rappelling ropes.
"It was right here a second ago . . ."
"Control the Great Conduit? You might as well try to divert a river with your hands."
"Aether is the soul of Kaladesh, and all souls should be free."
"Each creature holds a solution to a problem, a lesson to be learned." â€”Oviya Pashiri, sage lifecrafter
It is the nature of the strong to survive.
"The Great Conduit connects us all."
"It is folly to believe your precious inventions will endure. All things return to the soil." â€”Nirav, Tirahar elder
"I do not need to pierce your heart to still its beating."
"Regards from Peema." â€”Rishkar
The best engineers recognize when a problem has already been solved.
"I do not ask you to be tame. I only ask you to be true." â€”Rishkar, Peema renegade
"It was made, yes, but that does not mean it cannot grow."
"If nothing else, the Inventors' Fair taught us that we're only beginning to discover aether's true potential." â€”Kershan Danil, Highspire artisan
In the cellars beneath Narnam House, a strange and deadly garden grows.
"Wherever the strong would harm the weak, I will be there." â€”Ajani Goldmane
"I will not rest until every vestige of the Consulateâ€”every banner, flag, and standardâ€”has fallen."
Subtlety is not a necessary part of sabotage.
"The wild tangle of the Cowl provides sanctuary to life that watched the first buildings rise."
Its frill inspired the design of efficient aether collectors.
Gremlins are loyal to nothing but their next meal.
The residents of Embraal were never known for finesse, just for getting things done.
Perfect for getting through to the consuls.
The tools of invention became the weapons of revolution.
"Being an inventor means knowing how to use the tools at hand to make something greatâ€”or to bring it down." â€”Pia Nalaar
Illegal street races turned out to be perfect practice for avoiding Consulate patrols.
"I've made some fine acquisitions of late, so I'm planning to make commensurate improvements to my security systems. I have a consultant coming tomorrow." â€”Kurna Majan, Luminary League
"Let's add just a bit more stopping power."
"Hit where it hurts, and always hit first."
Pia's passion was directed at the big pictureâ€”at making real, lasting change.
"Catch me if you can."
Travelers to Lathnu, high on the Devra Cliffs, need not fear the political strife of Ghirapur . . . but they have other dangers to worry about.
"I was made for this!"
Aboard her ship, the Dragon's Smile, Kari follows no one's rules but her own.
Gremlins can change from pest to problem to plague in the span of a moment.
In the hold of the Heart of Kiran, Chandra answered Dovin Baan's sabotage with an explosive retort.
"Will you be strong and stand with me?"
The dragons perching in Freejam's towers symbolize the zone's fierce independence.
When fighting spilled over into Giant's Walk, the aether weapons and swooping airships angered the normally placid creatures.
"A well-made wrench is a versatile, indispensable tool."
"I don't think they'll appreciate my . . . adjustments." â€”Karavin, renegade saboteur
Chandra was driven by her anger, directed particularly at the man who had taken her father from her.
"The Consulate pushed me to my limit, darling, and this is the result."
"The time for subtlety is over, darling."
Some aetherborn joined the rebellion for profit, others for the sake of their freedom, still others for revenge.
There is no shortage of illegal salvage in Ghirapur, nor of those who are willing to profit from it.
When the salvage team brought in the shattered gearhulk, a wave of excitement swept through the renegade foundry.
You can't fight what you can't find.
Comrades in life. Comrades in death.
"Death might come tomorrow, but todayâ€”today I am alive."
As the rebellion spread, renegade ingenuity outpaced the Consulate's greatest fears.
"I am confident that all our enterprises can benefit from this little revolution."
A few aetherborn have discovered a way to sustain their own existences at the cost of an insatiable hunger for the life essence of other beings.
Renegades run the gamut from lofty sages to petty thieves.
Its buzzing is easily mistaken for the hum of a thopter's wings.
"Success is found where others fear to look." â€”Ara, renegade smuggler
"I didn't survive that crash just so I could fall to the likes of you."
Living so close to death gives the aetherborn an unusual perspective on risk.
Bitter the bite of a demon's steel, and deep the abyss it opens.
"This is bigger than you. All of you." â€”Tezzeret
"You never know what day might be your last."
Small aeronaut societies like the Wind-Kin had little to lose by siding with the renegades, and much to gain.
"The tools of the past will help us forge the future."
"You can tell me what I want to know, or you can talk to the Chief of Compliance. Why don't you make it easy on yourself?"
Escapes should always be daring.
Shipwrecks do wonders for the local fauna, providing both shelter and aether.
Conflict breeds opportunity.
A hermit crab goes through many shells in its lifetime, and not all are natural in origin.
The Hold, an illegal research facility in a derelict merchant ship, became a wellspring of renegade intelligence.
"Let's just broaden its surveillance lens."
"It is fascinating to see how the people of this plane replicate magical techniques without a natural gift. Also frustrating." â€”Jace Beleren
"Too little, too late. The machine is in motion." â€”Tezzeret
"Give me eight walkers, I'll give you the city." â€”Dovin Baan
The daredevil racers of the Derby Crows, long at odds with the Consulate, were quick to join the renegades in open revolt.
"When everything hangs on a single moment, be sure you choose the right moment." â€”Jace Beleren
"Slow the Consulate with whatever you've got!" â€”Jasi Ganin, master siphoner
"As a kid, I dreamed of flying on those wild drakes. They inspired me to build wings of my own." â€”Nadja Cloudtoucher, aerowright
For some of Ghirapur's aerowrights, building thopters is a byproduct of larger construction efforts.
As renegade forces closed in on the Aether Spire, Consulate blockades failed one by one.
"How easily your flames are quenched." â€”Baral, Chief of Compliance
"This armor transcends the limitations of mere flesh and bone."
"Get out of my way."
"The echo of silence is music to my ears."
"To survive up here, I've learned when to use my harpoon and when to just enjoy the view." â€”Kadhu, skywhaler
The Consulate's eyesâ€”unblinking, unsleepingâ€”are everywhere.
"It's important to always have the right tool for the job. This one is for picking my teeth."
"As this conflict grows, it gets harder to prevent the city from breaking down. How much longer can we keep this machinery balanced?"
"I can no longer sit in my workshop and ignore the events outside. My hammers strike for the people of Ghirapur."
Dwarves' tools are priceless heirlooms handed down through generations.
Many airship captains keep pets that share their love of the sky.
The loyalty of a felidar is hard won but worth the effort.
A living invention born of a grand design.
"With spy thopters all around, how can the consuls be so blind to Tezzeret's manipulations?" â€”Gideon Jura
"A key weakness in the design is its vulnerability to repeated, forceful blows."
"It seems there's even better hunting down here."
"It came to rest upon the angel's arm, and then the weight of their gazes fell upon me." â€”Aeronaut's journal
"Go forth and cause trouble, my little one!"
"There is no greater coward than one who believes in nothing."
"The workshops are silent. Our creations have been seized. They have killed what made us alive." â€”Pia Nalaar
